link.sbstck.com/redirect/76f23ec2-34a2-48a7-99bc-bb12371fe453?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B ,
Happy Tuesday!=20
There=E2=80=99s been a lot of debate about the importance of moats recently=
=2E Do startups have them, or not? Do startups need them, or not?=20
In my opinion, the conversation has lacked some depth and dimensionality, w=
hich has rendered it relatively useless for entrepreneurs and investors ali=
ke. I want to take a shot at clearing it up today.=20
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.=20
When to Dig a Moat
There=E2=80=99s a belief in tech that if you have the most talented team, t=
he best product, and the fastest growth =E2=80=93 that if you just Make Som=
ething People Want =E2=80=93 you don=E2=80=99t need to worry about moats.
That=E2=80=99s precisely wrong.=C2=A0
Companies that have the best products, most talented people, and fastest gr=
owth are precisely the ones for which moats are most important.=C2=A0
They=E2=80=99re the ones who might get lucky enough to have something to lo=
se. They=E2=80=99re the ones that bigger, better-resourced or smaller, fast=
er companies will one day compete with. And the faster they become successf=
ul, the faster they=E2=80=99ll face meaningful competition.=C2=A0
Success accelerates the need for moats. As soon as success seems obvious, s=
tartups lose their training wheels moat =E2=80=93 uncertainty =E2=80=93 and=
 should have at least the foundations of more permanent moats in place.=C2=
=A0
There=E2=80=99s simply less time to fuck around now, as many companies will=
 soon find out.=C2=A0=C2=A0
To set the foundation here, what are moats? In 7 Powers [ https://link.sbst=
ck.com/redirect/6d2331c9-e6fd-48ed-b376-829ff2847f0b?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ], Hamilton Helmer defines the=
m as =E2=80=9Cthose barriers that protect your business=E2=80=99 margins fr=
om the erosive forces of competition.=E2=80=9D He lists seven types: Econom=
ies of Scale, Network Effects, Counter-Positioning, Switching Costs, Brand,=
 Cornered Resource, Process Power. For definitions and examples of each, ch=
eck out Flo Crivello=E2=80=99s Mind the Moat [ https://link.sbstck.com/redi=
rect/6546deff-ee31-4306-a9df-ad836c8ec260?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA=
_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Moats won=E2=80=99t get you Product-Market Fit (PMF). You need that first b=
efore worrying about anything else, as USV=E2=80=99s Fred Wilson wrote in a=
 2013 blog post Product > Strategy > Business Model [ https://link.sbstck.c=
om/redirect/1a379e81-9878-4b10-bbe3-5732d2498f9d?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8=
J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. But by the time you have PMF, b=
y the time it=E2=80=99s obvious that what you=E2=80=99re doing could work, =
you should be able to protect it from the erosive forces of competition.=C2=
=A0
The ultimate goal of a venture-backed startup is to go public or get acquir=
ed for roughly $1 billion or more, not to get marked up by other VCs. That =
can take a long time, typically seven to ten years. Even if the startup lig=
hts a fire before competitors realize what it=E2=80=99s doing, it needs to =
protect and fan that fire for many years before a successful exit. For comp=
anies at which everything is going right, moats can be the difference betwe=
en IPO and cautionary tale.=C2=A0
Puja and I were watching Tour de France: Unchained on Netflix this weekend,=
 and I think Steve Chainel=E2=80=99s line on the cobblestone stage sums it =
up nicely:=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CYou can=E2=80=99t win the Tour de France on the cobblestones=E2=80=
=A6 but you can lose it.=E2=80=9D
This question about moats has come up a bunch recently in the context of ge=
nerative AI startups built on top of OpenAI=E2=80=99s APIs, ungenerously re=
ferred to as =E2=80=9CGPT Wrappers.=E2=80=9D On the one side are the VCs an=
d armchair analysts who believe that GPT Wrappers have no moats. On the oth=
er are the builders who say that building great products and growing quickl=
y is what matters most, and that moats will come later.=C2=A0
On Friday, The Information  [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/e8bae9db-f45=
5-4401-b392-f80fee68f8ca?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKb=
qOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]reported [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/e8bae9db-f455=
-4401-b392-f80fee68f8ca?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbq=
Osa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] that two generative AI companies, Jasper and Mutiny AI, w=
ere laying off employees. Jasper in particular had been growing very quickl=
y. Founded in 2021, before the AI Hype Cycle, it was on track to reach $75 =
million in revenue this year. Last October, it rode that growth to a $1.5 b=
illion valuation [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/4c29fdca-9537-4834-900c=
-1d65427cb204?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ]. Nine months later, it=E2=80=99s doing layoffs in the face of incre=
ased competition. It would seem that the company has not yet built deep eno=
ugh moats to protect its fast-growing prize. It=E2=80=99s only been alive t=
wo years. It=E2=80=99s hard to blame it.=C2=A0
What happened? Jasper simply ran out of uncertainty cover before it could b=
uild real moats. Let me explain.=C2=A0
In Productive Uncertainty [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/2eb5094c-b045-=
4b22-897e-91fb497a0adb?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqO=
sa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Jerry Neumann wrote that =E2=80=9Cthe only moat that can =
create excess value for a new startup is uncertainty=E2=80=9D because =E2=
=80=9Cuncertainty keeps competition at bay long enough for a moat to be bui=
lt.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
The more obvious your idea is and the easier it is to build, the faster you=
 need to dig moats. Conversely, the less obvious your idea is and the harde=
r it is to build, the longer you have to dig moats.=C2=A0
Whether you should spend all of your time on product or spend some of it on=
 strategy, even at an early stage, is a function of how much uncertainty ex=
ists in your business.=C2=A0
Neumann calls out two kinds of uncertainty: Novelty Uncertainty (~technical=
 risk) and Complexity Uncertainty (~market risk). Novelty Uncertainty is th=
e kind faced by a lot of deeptech companies: uncertainty over whether you c=
an actually build what you say you=E2=80=99re going to build. Complexity Un=
certainty assumes that you can build it, but questions whether there will e=
ver be a big and profitable market for it.=C2=A0
New startups have a limited window of time during which they=E2=80=99re pro=
tected by the cover of uncertainty to dig moats, and if they don=E2=80=99t =
dig them by the time others catch on, their excess profit will be competed =
away and they=E2=80=99ll struggle to achieve a good outcome.
Dumbing it down to a formula, you get something like this:=C2=A0
Depth of Moat Needed =3D How Obviously Good Your Idea Is - How Hard it is t=
o Build
The variables in this formula can and do change over time. Non-obvious idea=
s can become obvious as the market catches up to your insight and customers=
 prove you right with their wallets. Things that were once hard to build ca=
n become easier to build as infrastructure improves. One company's core tec=
hnology can become another=E2=80=99s API. It=E2=80=99s important for founde=
rs and investors alike to update the formula as the facts on the ground cha=
nge.=C2=A0
This formula explains startup truisms like =E2=80=9CGreat companies are bui=
lt in bear markets!=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9CYou need to be contrarian and rig=
ht.=E2=80=9D In both cases, increased uncertainty provides more time to bui=
ld defensibility.=C2=A0
If you=E2=80=99re in the =E2=80=9Cnew startups don=E2=80=99t need to worry =
about moats=E2=80=9D camp, you might point to success stories like Twitter =
and Airbnb, but those examples would miss the uncertainty angle.
In his blog post, Wilson used Twitter as an example of a company that found=
 PMF and then turned to strategy. Twitter was fortunate in that, even when =
people were using it, it started out looking like a toy [ https://link.sbst=
ck.com/redirect/5ab46ad5-bc89-4434-b9ed-bfc9ff87066c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ=
=2Egb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ]. Would-be competitors didn=
=E2=80=99t take a product that people used to share what they were eating f=
or lunch seriously enough to compete with until it was too late. We are sti=
ll dealing with the strength of the Network Effects Twitter was able to bui=
ld up under the cover of Complexity Uncertainty 17 years later.=C2=A0
Airbnb also focused exclusively on product at the expense of strategy in it=
s early days.=C2=A0
The Competitive Advantage slide in Airbnb=E2=80=99s pre-seed deck [ https:/=
/link.sbstck.com/redirect/0cfb43ef-1489-4608-8548-f7fb479ddae4?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] lists six product =
features and no real moats (unless you=E2=80=99re counting Brand, but that=
=E2=80=99s a very weak one until you have it).=C2=A0
There=E2=80=99s a reason that they were able to succeed despite that, and i=
t=E2=80=99s not just the brilliance of the product. It=E2=80=99s the fact t=
hat Airbnb seemed like a terrible idea! Airbnb had a really hard time raisi=
ng money. It faced rejection after rejection from VCs [ https://link.sbstck=
=2Ecom/redirect/1e9385cc-c7d2-43d9-974=
a-37d9eeacd151?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.g=
b8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. There=E2=80=99s probably a ru=
le in here somewhere: the easier it is for you to raise money, the more imm=
ediately you need moats.=C2=A0
Complexity Uncertainty gave Airbnb time to develop the Brand and Network Ef=
fects moats that have protected it all the way to that $91 billion market c=
ap. Ultimately, it spent a ton of time, money, and effort to build those mo=
ats =E2=80=93 it hired teams of people to finely balance supply and demand =
and worked with Disney to storyboard its guest experience, as two examples =
=E2=80=93 but given the amount of uncertainty around whether anyone would p=
ay to stay on someone else=E2=80=99s couch, they were right to focus on pro=
ving out the product before worrying about moats.
This is why the VCs and commentariat are jumping up and down about the lack=
 of moats in generative AI. There is practically no uncertainty.=C2=A0
Building on top of ChatGPT kills Novelty Uncertainty. I think everyone agre=
es on that. But the wild early success of so many generative AI products al=
so kills Complexity Uncertainty! If you build a generative AI product that =
starts to take off, you=E2=80=99re going to be attacked by other startups, =
bootstrapped companies, solo builders, and incumbents all hungry for your u=
sers.=C2=A0
Competition is inevitable. In a slower-moving or more technically novel spa=
ce, competition may be fine because you=E2=80=99ll have had time to build p=
roto-moats and customer loyalty. In a space that=E2=80=99s moving as quickl=
y as generative AI, the chances that you=E2=80=99ve dug strong enough moats=
 by the time that competitors come are slim.=C2=A0
In a piece titled Generative AI Companies Have Moats (Eventually) [ https:/=
/link.sbstck.com/redirect/b59f0eb5-8e16-4aa5-9dc8-66967d9a0917?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Battery Ventures=
=E2=80=99 Brandon Gleklen argued that it=E2=80=99s OK for generative AI com=
panies not to worry about moats, because like cloud companies before them, =
they can build them =E2=80=93 Scale Economies, in particular =E2=80=93 over=
 time as they listen to customers and evolve based on user feedback.=C2=A0
The point I=E2=80=99m trying to make is that that=E2=80=99s not true in a s=
pace as certain as generative AI. Eventually is a luxury for companies oper=
ating under uncertainty.=C2=A0
There will, of course, be very lucrative outcomes in AI when you zoom out f=
rom GPT wrappers. Two examples highlight the importance of digging moats du=
ring periods of uncertainty to protect yourself once the uncertainty lifts:=
 Hugging Face [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/a09aefa0-230d-4141-a3ce-c2=
922615e391?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] and Runway [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/e29449ed-691d-4771-879c-=
a68e387d516f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Exk=
RNpU ].=C2=A0
When Hugging Face was founded in 2016, back before AI was The Thing, its pr=
oduct was an AI chatbot built on top of its own NLP models. When the Attent=
ion is All You Need [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/d8a52cee-4d2a-4a29-9=
157-2c9d33be4cb7?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ] paper introduced the Transformer architecture the following year=
, the Hugging Face team created the Transformers [ https://link.sbstck.com/=
redirect/ac5103a1-fc98-451f-9c99-19e681067be8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T=
7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] open source library on GitHub, whic=
h took off in the open source community.=C2=A0
Hugging Face threw its full weight into becoming the =E2=80=9CGitHub for ma=
chine learning,=E2=80=9D hosting open source models and data sets, building=
 tools for users to build, train, and deploy those models, and fostering a =
community of developers.=C2=A0
Hugging Face used the five years that it operated under Complexity Uncertai=
nty =E2=80=93 before AI became the obvious thing =E2=80=93 to dig moats, th=
e most powerful of which is Network Effects. It=E2=80=99s rumored [ https:/=
/link.sbstck.com/redirect/cee0e239-afd1-454d-8201-53e3b9f3ac37?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] to have $30 - $50 =
million in revenue and to be raising a round at a $4 billion valuation.=C2=
=A0
If Hugging Face is an example of successfully using the time provided by Co=
mplexity Uncertainty to establish strong moats, Runway is a live situation:=
 can it dig moats before its Novelty Uncertainty shot clock expires?=C2=A0
Runway was also founded before the AI boom, in 2018, to build the =E2=80=9C=
world=E2=80=99s first end-to-end AI generation platform.=E2=80=9D It faced =
Novelty Uncertainty =E2=80=93 AI could barely generate images, let alone vi=
deos, in 2018. When it raised $2 million from Lux Capital, it did so at a m=
odest $9 million post-money valuation.=C2=A0
In the intervening five years, it=E2=80=99s built state-of-the-art video mo=
dels based on its own applied research. Recently, it announced the launch o=
f Gen-2, the best on the market:=C2=A0=C2=A0
In June, Runway raised [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/f8d85745-bc0e-4d4=
5-96cf-3fdb69c0cc7f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8=
-6m8ExkRNpU ] a $141 million round from Google, Nvidia, Salesforce and othe=
rs at a $1.5 billion valuation.=C2=A0
Because of how hard it is to build what Runway=E2=80=99s built, and the fac=
t that it only recently became apparent that it was possible, it=E2=80=99s =
been protected by Novelty Uncertainty to date. They=E2=80=99ve also shipped=
 products at a rapid clip to stay ahead. I=E2=80=99m not sure that the comp=
any has real moats yet, though, and it should act quickly to dig them befor=
e uncertainty runs out.=C2=A0
This is why strategy is important for startups, even if it=E2=80=99s uncool=
=2E At its simplest, early stage startu=
p strategy is about directing limited=20=
resources towards digging moats before you=E2=80=99ve removed enough uncert=
ainty to attract serious competition.=C2=A0
I=E2=80=99ve wanted to write a post defending strategy for a while, but I p=
romised myself I=E2=80=99d keep this one short and crisp, so I=E2=80=99ll s=
ave that for another post.=C2=A0
For now, what=E2=80=99s clear is that while not all startups need moats in =
the early days, they do need to start digging moats when their eventual suc=
cess is obvious to them but to very few others. If they=E2=80=99re lucky en=
ough to have something obviously worth attacking one day, moats will matter=
=2E=20
Get digging.=20
Thanks to Dan [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/e4322359-c89c-4d2b-bc2b-57=
aa40aeb014?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRN=
pU ] for editing!=20
That=E2=80=99s all for today! We=E2=80=99ll be back in your podcast feed to=
morrow and in your inbox with the Weekly Dose on Friday.=20
Thanks for reading,=20
Packy

