er it is to build, the longer you have to dig moats.&#160;</p><p style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;">Whether you should spend all of your time on product or spend some of =
it on strategy, even at an early stage, is a function of how much uncertain=
ty exists in your business.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Neumann calls out tw=
o kinds of uncertainty: Novelty Uncertainty (~technical risk) and Complexit=
y Uncertainty (~market risk). Novelty Uncertainty is the kind faced by a lo=
t of deeptech companies: uncertainty over whether you can actually build wh=
at you say you&#8217;re going to build. Complexity Uncertainty assumes that=
 you can build it, but questions whether there will ever be a big and profi=
table market for it.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size=
: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>New startups have a=
 limited window of time during which they&#8217;re protected by the cover o=
f uncertainty to dig moats, and if they don&#8217;t dig them by the time ot=
hers catch on, their excess profit will be competed away and they&#8217;ll =
struggle to achieve a good outcome.</strong></p><div class=3D"captioned-ima=
ge-container-static" style=3D"font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 3=
