 underline;">rejection after rejection from VCs</a><span>. There&#8217;s pr=
obably a rule in here somewhere: the easier it is for you to raise money, t=
he more immediately you need moats.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(=
64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span=
>Complexity Uncertainty gave Airbnb time to develop the Brand and Network E=
ffects moats that have protected it all the way to that $91 billion market =
cap. Ultimately, it spent a ton of time, money, and effort to build those m=
oats &#8211; it hired teams of people to finely balance supply and demand a=
nd worked with Disney to storyboard its guest experience, as two examples &=
#8211; but given the amount of uncertainty around whether anyone would pay =
to stay on someone else&#8217;s couch, they were right to focus on proving =
out the product </span><em>before</em><span> worrying about moats.</span></=
p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; m=
argin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>This is why the VCs and commentariat are jumping =
up and down about the lack of moats in generative AI. </span><strong>There =
is practically no uncertainty</strong><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px=
 0;">Building on top of ChatGPT kills Novelty Uncertainty. I think everyone=
 agrees on that. But the wild early success of so many generative AI produc=
ts also kills Complexity Uncertainty! If you build a generative AI product =
that starts to take off, you&#8217;re going to be attacked by other startup=
s, bootstrapped companies, solo builders, and incumbents all hungry for you=
r users.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Competition is inevitable. In a slower-=
moving or more technically novel space, competition may be fine because you=
&#8217;ll have had time to build proto-moats and customer loyalty. In a spa=
ce that&#8217;s moving as quickly as generative AI, the chances that you&#8=
217;ve dug strong enough moats by the time that competitors come are slim.&=
#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In a piece titled </span><em><a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.sbstck.com/redirect/b59f0eb5-8e16-4aa5-9dc8-66967d9a0917?j=3DeyJ=
1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">Generative AI Companies=
 Have Moats (Eventually)</a><span>, </span></em><span>Battery Ventures&#821=
7; Brandon Gleklen argued that it&#8217;s OK for generative AI companies no=
t to worry about moats, because like cloud companies before them, they can =
build them &#8211; </span><strong>Scale Economies</strong><span>, in partic=
ular &#8211; over time as they listen to customers and evolve based on user=
 feedback.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 1=
6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The point I&#8217;m trying to =
make is that that&#8217;s not true in a space as certain as generative AI. =
Eventually is a luxury for companies operating under uncertainty.&#160;</p>=
<p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; mar=
gin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>There will, of course, be very lucrative outcomes i=
n AI when you zoom out from GPT wrappers. Two examples highlight the import=
ance of digging moats during periods of uncertainty to protect yourself onc=
e the uncertainty lifts: </span><a href=3D"https://link.sbstck.com/redirect=
